Excellent! That is exactly right. You applied the Equality field (userId) before the Sort field (orderDate).

Deep Dive: The ESR Rule
In MongoDB, we follow the ESR (Equality, Sort, Range) rule to design the most efficient compound indexes:

Equality: Fields you match exactly (e.g., userId: "123").

Sort: Fields you use to order the results (e.g., orderDate: -1).

Range: Fields used for inequalities (e.g., price: { $gt: 500 }).

By putting userId first, MongoDB can jump straight to the "bucket" for that user. Because the orderDate is indexed within that bucket in descending order, the database can simply read the documents in order without having to perform an expensive "In-Memory Sort."